r the kitchen and watch the chefs at work — such a fun and fascinating way to start the evening! Our party of six was seated at a beautiful table by the window with stunning views, and from there the show began. Each dish was exquisitely prepared, with creative combinations and presentation that felt like art on a plate. The flavors were bold and inventive — definitely an experience for adventurous eaters who love exploring new tastes.\n\nThe service was outstanding throughout; the team took such wonderful care of us and made the night feel truly special. It was a memorable and joyful dining experience that we’ll be talking about for a long time.","time":"2 months ago"},{"author":"Anna","rating":5,"text":"Our experience at Akelarre was absolutely amazing. The food was exceptional — every dish was creative, beautifully presented, and full of incredible flavor. The staff were warm, attentive, and made us feel completely taken care of from start to finish. The atmosphere, the views, and the entire experience were unforgettable. Truly a 10/10 evening — we loved every moment and can’t wait to return!","time":"2 months ago"},{"author":"Alice Ho","rating":3,"text":"This is a hard one for me to rate as it is a Michelin 3* restaurant so naturally I am more critical and has higher expectations. But also because I don’t want them to feel pressured by my comments thus it took me a while to submit this review.\n\nHowever I feel as a 3*, it’s better that they accept every customer’s feedback or opinion.\n\nFirstly, we had a drink downstairs before the restaurant opened. When the table is ready, we had to bring our drinks up ourselves. I saw the same with other guests too. They should have bring it up for the guests instead. That to me is service.\n\nSecondly, my husband wasn’t too pleased they put us next to the stairs. If it’s full he rather not be able to make a reservation than to be placed by the front door next to the stairs.\n\nOverall, some food are really good, while some didn’t wowed us at all. I guess it normal to have varied taste but if it’s a place we would recommend or go back? Then the answer is no. We had both experienced 1 and 2 stars in our travels even in Amsterdam so to have our first 3* sub standard experience is quite disappointing.\n\nWhat puzzles me is also the extensive list of starters and desserts. Why do we need so many courses? Our tummies were bursting already from too much food to enjoy the rest of the dishes.\n\n3 things did stand out that night. The very friendly female server we had, the soft spoken sommelier and the fact that they took each table guests to visit their kitchen and spoke to the chef a little.","time":"5 months ago"},{"author":"The Global Gourmand","rating":4,"text":"What a wonderful location. The ambiance was exquisite. I loved the tour of the kitchen, and the staff was kind, especially the Mâitre ď.\n\nThey changed sommelier on us mid tasting menu, and the replacement didnt do a great job of telling us anything about the wine, which was a disappointment. More concerning were the 2 hairs I found in the food and the dirty fork I was presented with on the 4th course.\n\nThe food thematically consistent with local and seasonal trends, and the plating was what I generally what I expect at a 3 star restaurant .\n\nThe lobster and kiskilla, fried mullet, and white duck were memorable, the artichoke flower was a bit of a miss, but its soup with chard and foie gras helped balance the texture miss.","time":"4 months ago"},{"author":"Marius Fagerland","rating":3,"text":"Akelarre - Excellent food, but disappointing overall experience.\n\nAkelarre undoubtedly delivers on the food front - the tuna and hake were particularly exceptional, and the spectacular ocean views combined with the kitchen tour create a memorable atmosphere.\n\nUnfortunately, the experience was marred by logistical issues. Dinner started late and didn''t finish until 1 AM, which made the final courses less enjoyable. The wine service was also disappointing - we had to select wines ourselves without guidance, and weren''t prompted for refills, resulting in some of us sitting through two entire courses without wine.\n\nWith such high expectations for a 3-Michelin-star restaurant, we expected a more seamless experience. The food alone deserves recognition, but the service doesn''t match the stars in my opinion.","time":"4 months ago"}]'::jsonb,
