have ever toured. The historical detail in the introduction gives a story that makes each facet something to look forward to. The brochure is simple and easy to follow. The areas are well delineated and easy to find. The information is not repetitive or boring. The videos scattered throughout are interesting, well translated and highly entertaining.  The Swiss know what they are doing. I spent three hours just taking my time through this beautiful structure. I would pay and go again on my next visit.","time":"3 weeks ago"},{"author":"Lefteris Daflos","rating":5,"text":"A historic landmark of the region that really worth visiting when in the area!\nWell preserved castle with lots of interesting rooms, secret passages, caves, and stories to discover in every corner!\nThat was the second visit with the family, this time followed with another family, both with kids.\nEverybody (kids and adults) was excited and really enjoyed the visit.","time":"2 weeks ago"},{"author":"Alexander Vladimirov","rating":5,"text":"If you happen to visit the Swiss Riviera, I think it would be interesting to stop by Chillon Castle.\n\nThe castle of the Counts of Savoy has a long history that even reaches back to the Roman period. Like many castles, it changed hands over the centuries, though to remember all its owners, well, you''d have to be more of a castle enthusiast than an average tourist -)\n\nSo what''s interesting here?\n\nFirst, it is believed that Lord Byron visited the castle, and his \"signature\" supposedly still remains on a wall. Indeed, before chalk, paint, or markers became tools for self‑immortalization, people used to scratch their names into surfaces.\n\nSecond, I find it always fascinating to see how people lived long before our time. Think of giant fireplaces, large tables, uneven glass panes. Or, for instance, the toilets of that era - such everyday details are often awkwardly glossed over in history, but here they will tell you all about all that in detail.\n\nThird, the castle''s halls display some rather interesting contemporary artworks. On one hand, they are modern; on the other, they are somehow tied to themes of the Middle Ages, castles, mystery and romance.\n\nThere is also a good café on the castle grounds where you can enjoy a tasty and affordable meal. The menu of dishes and drinks is modest, but the food is good - hearty and delicious.\n\nYou can reach the castle by bus; they run along the coast.\n\nIt is a fascinating historical site, a place where you can enjoy yourself, learn something new, and glimpse the history of long‑gone eras, as well as the more recent Byronic period -)","time":"3 weeks ago"},{"author":"aki okuda","rating":5,"text":"The Timeless Majesty of Chillon Castle\n​Chillon Castle is a medieval masterpiece nestled on the rocky shores of Lake Geneva. As Switzerland’s most visited historic monument, it offers a perfect blend of breathtaking scenery and centuries of rich history.\n​History in Layers\nThe castle’s origins date back to the Bronze Age, but it gained prominence in the 12th century under the House of Savoy. Strategically located to control the road to the Great St. Bernard Pass, it served as a fortress, a summer residence, and later a state prison under Bernese rule. Its most famous inhabitant was François de Bonivard, the monk who inspired Lord Byron’s famous poem, The Prisoner of Chillon.","time":"2 weeks ago"},{"author":"Lorena","rating":4,"text":"Beautiful castle (Little Mermaid was inspired on it) with lots of history. I really recommend taking the audio guide which is super complete. It lets you wonder alone around the castle which is a magical experience.\n\nThe castle is in great conservation, and the dungeons are particularly beautiful. Would recommend this visit if you’re around.\n\nYou can buy tickets directly upon arrival, and the audio guide takes like 2h to complete","time":"2 months ago"}]'::jsonb,
