dth":2230,"height":1481,"attributions":["<a href=\"https://maps.google.com/maps/contrib/115012658929418046953\">Maison Buttin-de-Loës</a>"]},{"photo_reference":"AcnlKN18aQ2MsIVCSU1Tu2nWR2aBffVKSMrU86BabV07TUkgYisnEknVKwC8MMpx9on4rjAPXt4GAHuTgvkgZQcZGRH3xs7QSpYyYW1Ahm_yxnezriHWENquU-8KJl3GTQ92IwKgrj8kwsRO4je4Ind_bFQmD8hJgY6Cyq7hmPuyP6RLOCSRT3gAL5Nr3dfTFImIy8X7vtuoyNIdA_AdV6ea6tsQ7CxNkgz2WgsDwMe5o8weQBSbgWPYr37ltZLxnN78FEjqSqUMCuxWmWHjW15HKs9qVWNgfS84lVt5da1do7-XEw","width":1024,"height":629,"attributions":["<a href=\"https://maps.google.com/maps/contrib/115012658929418046953\">Maison Buttin-de-Loës</a>"]},{"photo_reference":"AcnlKN0Yrzy3NvqT_fak3bKoy_t4zwfr8GmVqpizwPSgQcxyX4KABFKiEKZ9SIkqqaGyDoWwqIgMeMN-xJSCHCqBgFTk3RljHsM-Kjj76iPo6Ei-KJE39NZ5uZ6PUpzIZX5ESIrJXTuNjstZz6qd8zlvODGsIN4Zn27kPfggQgbc148GmxQzO62HLM0WLFqrFhE1E9p53Pd5j7REBsd1dMv6H-8EfRhW-Xq730nUqb9U-R9rJ_pLAfJL-fGdZmnB_flBA-TVhLLTWm_1OAtqnfMLt3y2GjZZ7eOSm5LOLktm_YXvKg","width":1200,"height":792,"attributions":["<a href=\"https://maps.google.com/maps/contrib/115012658929418046953\">Maison Buttin-de-Loës</a>"]}]'::jsonb, '[{"author":"hew Goldingham","rating":5,"text":"The last time I visited this wonderful house I was in my teens.  A distant cousin, Marguerite de Loës, was living there and still showing visitors around in her nineties.  She and her husband had bought it sight unseen on the recommendation of an architect friend while living abroad (I believe in Nepal and Tibet - I remember being shown a roll of yellow Imperial Tibetan silk which they had brought back from their travels) on the recommendation of an architect friend, purely for the beauty of its situation.  At the time it was used for agricultural storage and the beauty of the rooms had yet to be revealed - amongst other features, the renaissance Room''s pillared fireplace surround  was hidden behind a false wall, its windows were bricked up and it was divided into small storage areas.  I picked blackberries in the terraced garden looking down over the lake while my mother and her sister chatted with their cousin.  Many decades have passed and in a few days time I will be back in Cully and looking forward to walking up to Grandvaux and revisiting this magical place.","time":"10 years ago"},{"author":"Yvan Pidoux","rating":5,"text":"Top","time":"4 years ago"},{"author":"Hugo Silva","rating":5,"text":"Top","time":"6 years ago"},{"author":"Jean Micol","rating":5,"text":"We rented the Renaissance room and garden for our wedding anniversary.\n\nWe have wonderful memories of this celebration.\nWe received a very warm welcome and excellent advice from the person in charge. We had a great working relationship.\n\nWe highly recommend this exceptional venue, but you need to book well in advance for weekend reservations.","time":"a month ago"},{"author":"Vanessa Dos Anjos","rating":2,"text":"Hello,\n\nThe venue deserves a 5/5.\nThe price a 5/5.\n\nWhat ultimately makes me give it a 2/5 is the stress caused by the house rules.\n\nFirst of all, we''re only allowed to rent the venue on the big day, starting in the morning at 9:00 a.m., not the evening before or whatever, to accommodate the bride and groom (which is often not the case with other reservations...).\nWe also have to return the keys the same day, if possible before sunset for the \"inventory\"...\nSo, we, who had only booked for one day, didn''t know all this in advance because we only learned about it after signing the reservation...\nWith benches and arches to set up and then remove EVERYTHING on the day itself, with the wedding already underway, I''ll let you imagine...\n\nThen, we also learned AFTER the visit, from the restaurant we were working with, that apparently we also had to move their tables, chairs, and umbrellas ourselves, AND put them back EXACTLY in place upon return, so on the same day... Because they didn''t inform us. So, once again, additional stress and organization to plan with family/friends...\n\nEspecially since I might add that given the aesthetics of these multicolored iron chairs/tables, it might be better to simply remove them? Especially since there''s nowhere provided for that! We need to find a \"spot.\"\n\nWhen I asked if there was a box and a microphone on site that we could possibly use for the ceremony, I was told no, and that I also have to be careful about \"the decibels.\"\n\nSo I finally said that, after a while, I think the house is renting the place, but that they should also make an effort because there are too many demanding criteria, expectations, etc. They told me, \"But you know, it''s a historic house and you''re not renting it for that much.\"\n\nTo which I retorted, \"Maybe for you it''s cheap, but for me, you''re making at least CHF 700 per day for rent with extraordinary standards, so you don''t even have to do a bit of cleaning or tidying up.\"\n\nWell, yes, if you don''t meet the criteria, apparently there are additional fees...\n\nI still had a beautiful wedding, but I wouldn''t go back, and if anyone wants to go, at least they should be well informed because for me, the whole thing was a real headache; it was the most complicated planning of my entire wedding.","time":"3 months ago"}]'::jsonb,
