u was built in 1854 for the banker Abraham de Rougemont. The design was by Pierre-Charles Dusillon, who followed the romantic neo-Gothic taste of the period. Its layout uses an asymmetrical plan, pointed arches, and decorative tracery.","time":"2 months ago"},{"author":"Antoni “Antek” Baranski","rating":5,"text":"If you want to stay here make sure you book well in advance as the castle has very few rooms and thus fills up quickly.\n\nThe rooms are big and spacious and if you don''t score one of the rooms on the lake side which have jaw dropping lake & mountain views, the ''simple'' garden view rooms will please you with views of big old oaks and other trees.\n\nMy only complaint would be the breakfast, it is small and uninspiring.","time":"3 months ago"},{"author":"UnDiplomatic Wife","rating":5,"text":"This park has everything! It was a joy to walk around. Everywhere we looked was beautiful.\n\nThey have toilets, boats that take you around (included in our card from the hotel I think), a ferry, amazing gardens, a train that goes around. Hope to see it tomorrow! The schedule is posted.\n\nThe highlight of course is the 180 yo castle that was just stunning! I felt like I traveled back in time but the facilities were modern.\n\nWe came buy for an afternoon snack and were not disappointed. That vanilla ice cream is something else and I used to work in an ice cream company. Already booked for our breakfast tomorrow. The staff are so lovely.\n\nIt was a treat to see the ferry & solar shuttle come by and a wedding in the castle!!\n\nWe also went back to have breakfast CHF 39/person & kids CHF 2 x age. So since my son is 9 x 2 =18 CHF for him. They make eggs the way you like it and crispy bacon. Bubbly is included for grown ups. Ask for the horseradish cream for the smoked salmon - absolutely the best I''ve ever had!\n\nWe also had lunch and the burger, fish and chips and chicken nuggets with fries were delicious. The fries especially crispy.\n\nHighly recommend this place! Worth every cent!","time":"6 months ago"}]'::jsonb,
