several times, at the bar and in the restaurant. It''s a must in St. Moritz!","time":"4 weeks ago"},{"author":"Darren Williamson","rating":5,"text":"Please see our trip advisor review but… this hotel is superb. Attention to detail is second to none and lots of added perks such as ski passes being included in the price. Expensive but a true Grand Hotel in quality, style and service","time":"2 weeks ago"},{"author":"Riccardo Solieri","rating":1,"text":"Negative Experience – Very Disappointing Stay\n\nI have been staying at the Palace Hotel in St. Moritz for about ten years, and this weekend I decided to try the Kulm, mainly attracted by its larger and more modern spa. Unfortunately, the experience was deeply disappointing.\n\nFirst, the welcome at reception was unprofessional. The staff member who checked us in spoke very poor English, gave confusing directions to the restaurants and spa that even took us to the wrong floor. When leaving the room, he remained standing  clearly expecting a tip – something I normally give willingly, but in this case felt inappropriate and uncomfortable.\n\nThe spa hygiene was unacceptable. External visitors were entering the spa still wearing outdoor shoes, covered in snow, as no one at the entrance enforced the use of shoe covers. This is a serious hygiene issue. Inside the nude sauna, where swimsuits are explicitly forbidden, guests consistently entered wearing them despite clear signage, and the spa staff did nothing to correct this. Upon returning to Milan, I had to see a dermatologist and was diagnosed with a form of dermatitis likely caused by the poor hygiene standards.\n\nThe temperature in the corridors leading to the spa was extremely cold. All radiators were set to the minimum, forcing us to walk through the hotel in bathrobes in uncomfortable conditions. My partner developed a fever once we returned home.\n\nFinally, the management’s response to our complaints was disappointing. For a stay of around 3,000 CHF for two nights, the only compensation offered was the removal of a single 12-CHF tea charge from the bar. Given the seriousness of the issues, at the very least the bar drinks or the parking fees could have been waived.\n\nOverall, the experience fell far below the expectations for a luxury hotel in St. Moritz. Unfortunately, I cannot recommend Kulm and will be returning to the Palace for future stays.","time":"a month ago"},{"author":"Marika Sorichetti","rating":5,"text":"The Kulm Hotel in St. Moritz is truly one of the best hotels in town. From the moment you step into the lobby, you’re greeted with one of the most breathtaking views over the lake — a scene so beautiful it almost feels magical.\n\nThe staff are exceptionally welcoming, attentive, and genuinely careful with every detail, making you feel at home instantly. Their ability to switch seamlessly between languages (Italian, English, French, Dutch) adds to the sense of effortless hospitality.\n\nFood and drinks are a delight: everything is flavorful and well-prepared. The tea I tried, with its rich red-fruit notes, was perfectly balanced, and the apple cake was intense, aromatic, and memorable.\n\nThe atmosphere is elevated even further by live music, creating a relaxing environment where time seems to slow down. Sitting there, with the view and the music, you can’t help but want to stay forever.\n\nA place where elegance meets warmth — the Kulm is St. Moritz at its finest.","time":"4 months ago"}]'::jsonb,
